
Here are several GIF packages related to the detector-present solution of the time-dependent Schrödinger equation for a Gaussian spinor wave packet in a harmonic waveguide.

The simulations use a spin-coupled absorbing boundary condition (spinor ABC) at the detecting roof \(z=L_z\). The lower face and artificial transverse faces are hard-wall/Dirichlet boundaries. The bulk Hamiltonian is spin-independent and contains harmonic transverse confinement. The initial state is a factorized Gaussian wave packet,
\[
\Psi_0(x,y,z)=\chi_\omega(x,y)\,\phi_0(z)\,\eta,
\]
where \(\chi_\omega\) is the transverse harmonic ground state, \(\phi_0\) is a longitudinal Gaussian packet, and \(\eta\) is the initial spinor.

Each ZIP contains visualization outputs such as:

- `isosurf.gif`: 3D isosurface visualization of the probability density  
  \[
  \rho=|\psi_\uparrow|^2+|\psi_\downarrow|^2 .
  \]

- `midplanes.gif`: density slices through representative coordinate planes.

- `scatter.gif`: scatter-style visualization of the evolving density.

- `slices_bar.gif`: longitudinal \(z\)-slice marginal,
  \[
  P_z(z_k,t)=\sum_{i,j}\rho(x_i,y_j,z_k,t)\,\Delta x\,\Delta y\,\Delta z .
  \]
  This diagnostic integrates over \(x,y\), so it shows the longitudinal probability distribution only. It is useful for checking that the early longitudinal marginal is essentially unchanged across the \(\omega\)-sweep. The transverse narrowing is shown instead by the midplane and isosurface movies.

- `rho.png`: representative density snapshot.

- `simulation_log.txt` and `stdout.txt`: run parameters and numerical log information.

The visualization files are intended as diagnostics of the detector-present spinor-ABC evolution. They are not additional detector models and should be read together with the roof-flux and finite-window statistics discussed in the paper.
